# Feature: Hierarchical Work Item Tree (Goals → Tasks)

## Goal
Extend the existing Work Item View so it can display and navigate the full hierarchical chain of work items:

**Goal → Objective → Epic → Feature → PBI → Task**

This view provides a structured, read-only overview of all work items derived from one or more configured goals.

---

## Functional Description

### 1. Data Scope, Modes, and Persistence

- The application supports configuring one or more **Goals** in the **Settings screen**.
- The **Settings screen** also contains a setting to select the active **data mode**:
  - **Mock mode**
  - **TFS mode**
- The selected mode is persisted and determines the active data source at runtime.

- When the **Pull & Cache Data** action is triggered:
  - All configured Goals are loaded.
  - All child work items are loaded **recursively** down to Task level.
- Data is loaded **only** when this action is explicitly triggered.
- Loaded data is cached locally and treated as **read-only** until reloaded.

#### Data Modes

- **Mock mode**
  - Uses static test data.
  - Mock data contains the same fields as the current implementation.
- **TFS mode**
  - Pulls real data from the configured TFS server.

#### Mode Isolation

- Persisted UI state **must be isolated per data mode**.
- At minimum, the following state is stored **separately for Mock and TFS mode**:
  - Tree expand/collapse state
  - Current selection (including multi-selection)
- Switching modes:
  - Does not reuse cached data from another mode.
  - Does not reuse persisted UI state from another mode.
  - Always operates on the data and state belonging to the currently selected mode.

---

### 2. Tree View Structure

- Work items are displayed in a **tree view** representing the parent–child hierarchy.
- Each node represents a single work item.
- The tree view:
  - Supports expand/collapse per node.
  - Persists collapse/expand state across reloads where possible (best-effort based on stable work item identity within the same mode).
  - Supports **multi-selection** (keyboard and mouse).
  - Is keyboard-navigable from the start.
  - Fits seamlessly within the existing application theme and visual language.
- Accessibility (ARIA) is not required at this stage, except where needed for automated testing.

---

### 3. Columns, Status, and Layout

- The tree view is **column-based**, not a single text column.
- Each work item has an explicit **status**.
- At minimum, the tree view contains the following columns:
  - **Type icon column**
  - **Title column**
  - **Status column**
  - **Validation / status icon column**
- Column layout must be extensible to support additional fields in future iterations.
- Columns are visually aligned across all hierarchy levels.

#### Status Handling

- In **Mock mode**, each work item uses one of the following statuses:
  - `New`
  - `In Progress`
  - `Done`
- Status is shown in the **Status column**.
- In a future iteration:
  - Status values will differ per work item type.
  - Status values will be sourced directly from TFS.
  - The tree view must not assume a fixed or global status set.

---

### 4. Work Item Type Indicators

Each work item displays a small colored square icon **before the title**, indicating its type:

| Work Item Type | Color        |
|---------------|--------------|
| Goal          | Green        |
| Objective     | Light green  |
| Epic          | Orange       |
| Feature       | Purple       |
| PBI           | Blue         |
| Task          | Yellow       |

---

### 5. Validation Status Indicators

- At the **end of each row**, validation status icons may be displayed.
- Each icon represents a specific validation fault category.
- Multiple icons per item are allowed.

---

### 6. Detail View Integration (Single & Multi-Select)

- Clicking a work item selects it and updates the **detail view**.
- Multiple work items can be selected simultaneously.

#### Detail View Behavior

- When **a single item** is selected:
  - The detail view shows all available fields for that work item.
- When **multiple items** are selected:
  - The detail view only shows fields whose values are **identical across all selected items**.
  - Fields with differing values are:
    - Shown in a disabled state.
    - Accompanied by a clear explanatory message indicating that the field cannot be shown or edited due to multi-selection.
- Below the field section, a separate area lists validation warnings and errors:
  - Each entry includes an icon and descriptive text.
- The entire detail view remains read-only in this feature.

---

## Non-Functional Constraints

- No write-back to TFS.
- No automatic refresh or background updates.
- All data remains static until explicitly reloaded.
- Tree view and detail view must be structured for future expansion (additional fields, validations, statuses, and item types).
